@startuml llm-request-flow
' An LLM call end to end: auth, routing, budget, rate limit, forward, and usage extraction.
' Source of truth: docs/src/gateways/llm/request-handling.md
!include _style.puml

participant "Agent\ncontainer" as agent
participant "LLM Gateway\n:8443" as gw #90EE90
participant "Informer cache\nPod / Agent /\nModelProvider" as inf #F5F5F5
participant "Secret\n(kaalm-system)" as sec #FFD580
participant "Upstream\nprovider" as prov #FFE4B5

agent -> gw : **1.** HTTPS to $KAALM_GATEWAY_ENDPOINT\nnative provider path + qualified\n{providerRef}/{modelId}
opt body > maxLLMRequestBodyBytes (4 MiB)
  gw --> agent : **413** request_too_large\n(at the listener, **before** namespace identification)
end

gw -> gw : **2a.** Authenticate:\nmTLS client-cert SAN (Mode 1)\nor TokenReview bearer (Mode 2)
gw -> inf : **2b.** Cross-check: Pod at source IP
inf --> gw : Pod namespace
note over gw, inf
  **Authenticate first, then cross-check.**
  Authentication establishes the namespace claim.
  The source-IP lookup confirms the claim came
  from where it should have. It is defense in
  depth, not the identity mechanism.
end note

gw -> inf : **3.** Pod ownerRef -> Agent,\nread spec.providers;\nparse provider/model
gw -> inf : **4.** Validate: namespace in allowedNamespaces\n(else 403), then model in ModelProvider.models (else 400)
gw -> gw : **5.** Budget check\ndegrade -> rewrite model name\nblock -> error to agent
gw -> gw : **6.** Rate limit: per-(namespace, model)\ntoken bucket, req/min + tokens/min

gw -> sec : **7a.** read provider credential
sec --> gw : API key, or Vertex OAuth2 token

note over gw #FFE4B5
  **7b. The forwarded-header contract**
  ....
  **STRIP before injecting the credential:**
  Authorization, x-api-key, api-key.
  Header names differ per provider and per tier,
  so injection alone would leave a live SA token
  in place and forward it to the provider.
  ....
  **DROP hop-by-hop, per RFC 7230 6.1:**
  Connection, TE, Upgrade, Proxy-Authorization.
  ....
  **PIN Accept-Encoding: identity.**
  Go only auto-decompresses gzip it negotiated
  itself, so relaying a caller's gzip would make
  step 9 unreadable and zero all spend silently.
end note

gw -> prov : **7c.** forward, provider prefix stripped\n(on failure: walk the fallback chain,\nup to maxFallbackDepth)
prov --> gw : provider response\n(SSE chunks arrive incrementally)
gw --> agent : **8.** response relayed to the agent\n(chunks forwarded as they arrive)

note over gw, prov
  **9. Usage extraction, on the return leg**
  ....
  Anthropic: usage.input_tokens / output_tokens
  OpenAI: usage.prompt_tokens / completion_tokens
  Vertex: usageMetadata.promptTokenCount
  and candidatesTokenCount
  ....
  Actual usage from the response always beats
  pre-call estimation. Streaming reads it from
  the usage-bearing SSE events instead.
end note
gw -> gw : **10.** update the in-process\nspend counter for the namespace
@enduml
